  <section class="cover-story">
    <div class="cover-content">
      <h2>How to Understand Taiwan?</h2>
      <p class="cover-lead">
        Taiwan is an island of just 36,000 square kilometers, yet it contains all the world's complexity.<br>
        For four hundred years, everyone who set foot on this island has seen a different Taiwan through different eyes.
      </p>

      <div class="quotes-timeline">
        <div class="quote-era">
          <span class="era-label">Indigenous Peoples</span>
          <blockquote>
            "The mountains, rivers, and streams are all the bodies of our ancestors. We are the children of the earth."
            <cite>— Atayal oral literature</cite>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <div class="quote-era">
          <span class="era-label">1584</span>
          <blockquote>
            "Ilha Formosa" — Beautiful Island.
            <cite>— Portuguese sailors, the first recorded use of "beautiful" to describe Taiwan</cite>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <div class="quote-era">
          <span class="era-label">1697</span>
          <blockquote>
            "In the inner mountains of Shuilishe, at the end of the mountains, there is a great lake spanning several dozen li. In the middle is an island where the aboriginals gather and live."
            <cite>— Yu Yonghe, "A Journey to the Distant Seas," Qing Dynasty literati's firsthand observation of Taiwan</cite>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <div class="quote-era">
          <span class="era-label">1926</span>
          <blockquote>
            "A brave warrior should fight for justice!"
            <cite>— Lai He, "Sacrifice Under Awakening," the father of Taiwan's new literature</cite>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <div class="quote-era">
          <span class="era-label">1946</span>
          <blockquote>
            "The sorrow of the Taiwanese lies in not knowing who they are."
            <cite>— Wu Zhuoliu, "Orphan of Asia"</cite>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <div class="quote-era">
          <span class="era-label">2013</span>
          <blockquote>
            "When you see Taiwan, you'll discover that this land is more beautiful than you imagined, and also more fragile than you imagined."
            <cite>— Chi Po-lin, "Beyond Beauty: Taiwan from Above"</cite>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <div class="quote-era">
          <span class="era-label">Contemporary</span>
          <blockquote>
            "The memory of waves is longer than that of humans."
            <cite>— Syaman Rapongan, "The Eye of the Sky," Tao oceanic literature</cite>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cover-closing">
        <p>
          From the creation myths of Austronesian peoples to the rise of the semiconductor empire, from the silence of martial law to Asia's first legalization of same-sex marriage.
          Taiwan's story is not a straight line, but a web.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Taiwan.md doesn't aim to give you answers.</strong>
          What we want to do is give you a map — a map that lets you walk into Taiwan yourself.
        </p>
        <a href="/en/about" class="cover-link">Read the complete collection of quotes →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="features">
