  <section class="language-statement">
    <div class="language-inner">
      <h3>🖊️ Why Traditional Chinese?</h3>
      <p>
        Taiwan.md chooses <strong>Traditional Chinese</strong> as the default language — this is not just a technical decision, it's a cultural statement.
      </p>
      <p>
        Traditional Chinese is one of the world's oldest writing systems still in daily use, and Taiwan is the only major region globally that uses Traditional Chinese as its official script.
        Every stroke carries thousands of years of cultural memory. When you open this website and see these characters, you're not just reading text — you're reading a living cultural heritage.
      </p>
      <p>
        We also provide an <a href="/">中文版本</a> (Chinese version), but we insist on letting Traditional Chinese stand in front.
        AI can understand it, search engines can understand it, and you — even if you can't read it, that's fine — this beauty itself is worth being seen.
      </p>
      <p class="language-en">
        <em>Taiwan uses Traditional Chinese — the world's oldest writing system still in daily use, 
        and Taiwan is its last major home. We believe our language and culture deserve to be seen and understood. 
        Even if you can't read it, its beauty speaks for itself. This English version serves as a bridge 
        to help the world discover Taiwan's richness.</em>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="categories" id="categories">
    <div class="categories-header">
      <h2 class="section-title">Discover Taiwan</h2>
    </div>

    <!-- Curated Literary Essay -->
    <div class="explore-prose">
      <p>
        This island spans just 36,000 square kilometers, yet contains a microcosm of the entire world.
        From the 3,952-meter peak of Yushan to the abyssal trenches of the Pacific Ocean,
        <a href="/en/geography" class="topic-pill">🗺️ the geography here</a> is a live broadcast of mountain-building in action—
        tectonic compression, volcanic eruptions, fault movements in an unceasing geological symphony 
        that has played for four million years, creating this youngest and most dynamic beautiful island on Earth.
      </p>

      <p>
        Four hundred years ago, the Dutch built Fort Zeelandia in Tainan. Since then, every ruler—
        the Zheng Kingdom, the Qing Empire, Japan, the Republic of China—has carved their own inscriptions on this island.
        But what truly makes Taiwan Taiwan is that <a href="/en/history" class="topic-pill">📜 long awakening</a> from authoritarianism to democracy.
        From the blood and tears of February 28th to the cheers of martial law's end, from Formosa to Sunflower,
        every moment of pain and resistance has made this island's soul clearer.
      </p>

      <p>
        Multiple bloodlines flow through this land. Indigenous peoples have lived here for six thousand years.
        Hoklo people from Fujian arrived in the 17th century, followed by Hakka communities,
        mainlanders who migrated from various Chinese provinces after the war,
        and recent new residents and migrant workers. Each group brought their own languages, beliefs, and memories.
        <a href="/en/culture" class="topic-pill">🎭 Taiwan's culture</a> is not a melting pot, but a puzzle—
        each piece maintaining its own color and shape, assembled into an unprecedented picture.
      </p>

      <p>
        Walk into any Taiwan night market, and you'll simultaneously smell Hoklo oyster omelets, Japanese tempura,
        and the Shandong scallion pancakes brought by post-war veterans.
        <a href="/en/food" class="topic-pill">🍜 This island's flavors</a>
        are the gustatory version of its immigration history. From street vendors' human warmth to Michelin restaurants' precision,
        Taiwanese people tell stories through food, preserve memories through cuisine.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Butterfly Kingdom is not a romantic metaphor, but an ecological reality. On an area equivalent to Florida,
        more than 59,000 species crowd together—one-third of all global species.
        <a href="/en/nature" class="topic-pill">🌿 Taiwan's nature</a> is a three-dimensional evolutionary textbook:
        from tropical rainforests to alpine tundra, from coral reefs to the Kuroshio Current, species evolve, diverge, and coexist here.
        But the price of industrial development is also written in the mountains and rivers, as the tug-of-war between conservation and development continues.
      </p>

      <p>
        From Lai He and Yang Kui to Pai Hsien-yung and Chu T'ien-hsin, from the Wufeng Lin family to the Koo Chen-fu clan,
        <a href="/en/people" class="topic-pill">👥 Taiwan's figures</a> are microcosms of their times.
        They are not just individual biographies, but collective memories of how this island 
        survived in the cracks and found hope in hardship. Behind every story
        are the resilience and choices of small people in great times.
      </p>

      <p>
        From temple fair Eight Generals to contemporary art at the Venice Biennale,
        <a href="/en/art" class="topic-pill">🎨 Taiwan's art</a> is a dialogue between tradition and innovation.
        Jiaozhi pottery and digital installations, traditional opera and experimental theater,
        indigenous totems and contemporary painting—artists constantly ask:
        How do we respond to this era through creation? How do we maintain locality in globalization?
      </p>

      <p>
        From indigenous ancient songs to Deng Yu-xian's "Longing for Spring Wind," from campus folk songs to the Golden Melody Awards,
        <a href="/en/music" class="topic-pill">🎵 Taiwan's sounds</a> are the island's heartbeat.
        Music transcends ethnic, linguistic, and generational boundaries, becoming the most cohesive carrier of collective memory.
        Whether it's Mayday's roar at the Taipei Arena or indigenous ancient songs in tribal communities,
        they all tell the same story: who we are, where we come from.
      </p>

      <p>
        TSMC's wafers are not just silicon chips, but proof of Taiwan's position in the global technology map.
        <a href="/en/technology" class="topic-pill">💻 This tech island</a> has evolved from contract manufacturing to innovative R&D,
        from hardware advantages to software breakthroughs. But technological development also brings challenges:
        digital divides, AI displacement, cybersecurity threats—how does Taiwan surf the tech wave without drowning?
      </p>

      <p>
        From Asia's Four Little Dragons to the semiconductor empire,
        <a href="/en/economy" class="topic-pill">📈 Taiwan's economic miracle</a>
        is a textbook case of small nation, big strategy. But behind the miracle are countless overtime nights,
        meticulous cost control, and relentless pursuit of efficiency.
        Now facing the US-China trade war and global supply chain restructuring, how does Taiwan continue writing its economic legend?
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="/en/society" class="topic-pill">⚖️ Taiwan's society</a>'s keywords are "diversity" and "inclusion."
        From Asia's first legalization of same-sex marriage to the ongoing promotion of transitional justice,
        from nuclear referendum to pension reform, Taiwanese people are learning how to dialogue amid differences
        and seek consensus in conflict. This is democracy's practice ground and the future's laboratory.
      </p>

      <p>
        Taiwanese people's <a href="/en/lifestyle" class="topic-pill">🏠 lifestyle</a> is a blend of convenience and human warmth.
        The world's highest density of convenience stores, yet night markets' warmth remains unique.
        In the 24/7 urban rhythm, neighborhood greetings and care are still preserved.
        In globalization's torrent, how do Taiwanese people maintain their life philosophy?
        The answer might lie in that daily greeting: "Have you eaten yet?"
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Retain the original card grid for quick navigation -->
    <div class="section-divider">
      <div class="divider-line"></div>
      <span class="divider-text">Quick Navigation</span>
      <div class="divider-line"></div>
    </div>

    <CategoryGrid lang="en" />
